the best one to try and break.

00:44:00.460 --> 00:44:02.830
And once you've
actually made clear

00:44:02.830 --> 00:44:04.539
what all the connections are--

00:44:04.539 --> 00:44:06.580
this is a bit like a
cognitive behavioral therapy

00:44:06.580 --> 00:44:09.160
technique, where you try and
see which arrow you can break--

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:11.807
but it is about seeing
which one is the weakest

00:44:11.807 --> 00:44:14.140
or which one would be the
easiest one to try and change.

00:44:14.140 --> 00:44:15.350
And then, you can try it.

00:44:15.350 --> 00:44:16.480
And if it doesn't
work that well,

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:18.230
at least you might
have weakened it a bit.

00:44:18.230 --> 00:44:20.230
And then, you can try
weakening another one.

00:44:20.230 --> 00:44:21.646
And then eventually,
there will be

00:44:21.646 --> 00:44:24.460
enough that has become weaker
that the end result doesn't

00:44:24.460 --> 00:44:25.600
happen quite so strongly.

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:31.940
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for this amazing talk,

00:44:31.940 --> 00:44:32.960
I really enjoyed it.

00:44:32.960 --> 00:44:34.130
EUGENIA CHENG: Thank you.

00:44:34.130 --> 00:44:36.710
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering about--

00:44:36.710 --> 00:44:39.380
so obviously, we would
all be better off

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:42.697
if we all used such logical
mathematical constructs,

00:44:42.697 --> 00:44:45.030
but I think it's clear that,
especially on the internet,

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:46.970
a lot of people do not.

00:44:46.970 --> 00:44:48.980
I was wondering,
are you optimistic,

00:44:48.980 --> 00:44:55.100
or do you have any tips for how
we can engage people via logic

00:44:55.100 --> 00:44:57.860
if they're not, even at
all, willing to acknowledge

00:44:57.860 --> 00:45:00.200
that maybe that's a
helpful thing to do?

00:45:00.200 --> 00:45:02.900
EUGENIA CHENG: I am optimistic,
and that's why I'm here,

00:45:02.900 --> 00:45:04.566
and that's why I write
books, and that's

00:45:04.566 --> 00:45:07.160
why I'm in education, because
I am optimistic that we

00:45:07.160 --> 00:45:08.750
can change things.

00:45:08.750 --> 00:45:14.690
I think that there are some very
extreme people who we might not

00:45:14.690 --> 00:45:17.540
be able to reach immediately,
and that that's OK,

00:45:17.540 --> 00:45:19.780
and we shouldn't get too
upset about those people.

00:45:19.780 --> 00:45:21.530
But there are a whole
load of other people

00:45:21.530 --> 00:45:24.470
who aren't so far gone.

00:45:24.470 --> 00:45:27.680
We shouldn't start with the most
absolutely difficult people.

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:30.350
But there are other people
who are, first of all,

00:45:30.350 --> 00:45:33.000
there are people who really,
really want to do better

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:34.190
but don't know how.

00:45:34.190 --> 00:45:37.220
And those are people we can
definitely help to do better.

00:45:37.220 --> 00:45:40.922
Then, are the people who
aren't really terrible people,

00:45:40.922 --> 00:45:43.130
they just don't have the
techniques or don't realize.

00:45:43.130 --> 00:45:44.870
And then once you
explain it to them,

00:45:44.870 --> 00:45:49.220
just like with
things like sexually

00:45:49.220 --> 00:45:52.940
inappropriate comments, some
men, especially older ones,

00:45:52.940 --> 00:45:55.797
have just got used to the fact
that they can say those things

00:45:55.797 --> 00:45:56.880
and they don't understand.

00:45:56.880 --> 00:45:58.504
But they're not really
terrible people,

00:45:58.504 --> 00:46:00.600
and once you explain it
to them, then they get it,

00:46:00.600 --> 00:46:01.641
and then they can change.

00:46:01.641 --> 00:46:03.980
Whereas the ones who are
really absolutely morons,

00:46:03.980 --> 00:46:06.320
maybe we can't change
them yet, but eventually,

00:46:06.320 --> 00:46:08.600
if we sway enough people
in that direction.

00:46:08.600 --> 00:46:10.760
So I see it as being
a kind of continuum,

00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:12.320
and that these are
the people that we

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:15.710
can most easily convince,
and then once we convinced

00:46:15.710 --> 00:46:17.360
these people, then
everything will

00:46:17.360 --> 00:46:19.130
have shifted a bit further
this way so that then we

00:46:19.130 --> 00:46:20.330
can convince these people.

00:46:20.330 --> 00:46:21.600
And then everything
will shift this way,

00:46:21.600 --> 00:46:22.975
and we can convince
these people.

00:46:22.975 --> 00:46:24.590
And eventually,
everything will shift,

00:46:24.590 --> 00:46:26.720
and then maybe we can
get back to a situation

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:29.360
where it is not acceptable
to be those people anymore.

00:46:29.360 --> 00:46:31.360
And one of the problems
with the current climate

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:35.480
is that it has become acceptable
again to be those people.

00:46:35.480 --> 00:46:38.445
And they probably
were always there,

00:46:38.445 --> 00:46:40.820
but maybe they felt like they
weren't supposed to show it

00:46:40.820 --> 00:46:43.650
or that they was not supposed
to be really like that.

00:46:43.650 --> 00:46:46.312
And if we can persuade everyone
to come a bit further back

00:46:46.312 --> 00:46:48.770
that way, I don't think we have
to just flip everybody over

00:46:48.770 --> 00:46:49.520
overnight.

00:46:49.520 --> 00:46:52.320
But if we can shift the
balance a bit further,

00:46:52.320 --> 00:46:55.160
then I think that could
just flip it back again.

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:57.260
And yes, I am optimistic.

00:46:57.260 --> 00:47:00.380
The people who are
unreasonable on the internet

00:47:00.380 --> 00:47:02.900
are often the loudest
and the most annoying,

00:47:02.900 --> 00:47:06.000
but I don't think that they're
the majority of people.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:09.140
And I've seen enough reasonable
conversations on Twitter, even,

00:47:09.140 --> 00:47:12.410
that I believe it is possible
if we all slow down a bit

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:14.724
and try to understand what
other people are thinking,

00:47:14.724 --> 00:47:17.140
rather than immediately trying
to show that they're wrong.

00:47:22.750 --> 00:47:25.190
AUDIENCE: You are an
accomplished artist as well.

00:47:25.190 --> 00:47:28.690
And your title of your
book [? says ?] about art.

00:47:28.690 --> 00:47:32.452
So where does the art play a
role in making sense of things?

00:47:32.452 --> 00:47:34.890
EUGENIA CHENG: Oh, thank you.

00:47:34.890 --> 00:47:36.244
I think that anything is an art.

00:47:36.244 --> 00:47:38.410
Well, it's interesting,
because I teach art students

00:47:38.410 --> 00:47:39.970
at the school of the Art
Institute of Chicago,

00:47:39.970 --> 00:47:42.160
so we've had many
discussions about what art is

00:47:42.160 --> 00:47:43.480
and what science is.

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:46.180
And what we have collectively
decided one semester

00:47:46.180 --> 00:47:49.030
is that science is about
trying to understand

00:47:49.030 --> 00:47:51.130
the world around us,
and that art is about

00:47:51.130 --> 00:47:53.040
trying to interpret
the world around us,

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:54.790
and that in order to
understand the world,

00:47:54.790 --> 00:47:56.020
you have to interpret it.

00:47:56.020 --> 00:47:57.160
And in order to
interpret the world,

00:47:57.160 --> 00:47:58.243
you have to understand it.

00:47:58.243 --> 00:48:00.340
So they're really
joined together,

00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:01.810
they're not completely separate.

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:05.730
And to me, something
becomes an art

00:48:05.730 --> 00:48:08.800
if it's not an algorithmic
process that you just

00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:09.884
follow step-by-step.

00:48:09.884 --> 00:48:11.800
And that's why there is
an art to using logic.

00:48:11.800 --> 00:48:13.960
Because if you were
just doing, say,

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:17.259
computer-aided proofs
of something, then maybe

00:48:17.259 --> 00:48:19.300
the computer wouldn't be
using an art, because it

00:48:19.300 --> 00:48:20.650
would be using an algorithm.

00:48:20.650 --> 00:48:24.190
But when we're
using logic, we have

00:48:24.190 --> 00:48:25.930
to understand the
people around us,

00:48:25.930 --> 00:48:28.000
and we have to engage
emotions, and we

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.460
have to pick ways
of speaking, and we

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:33.460
have to use techniques to
understand what's going on.

00:48:33.460 --> 00:48:35.430
And that, to me, is
what makes it an art.

